The Oswego City School District will be holding a Board of Education meeting on Tuesday, Sept. 1, 2020.

Executive Session at 4:30 p.m. for the purpose of discussions regarding proposed, pending, or current litigation.

Regular Session will then start at 5 p.m.

Executive Session at the end of the regular session for the purpose of matters leading to the appointment, employment, promotion, demotion, discipline, suspension, dismissal or removal of a particular person or corporation.

This meeting will be live-streamed and will also be available on Channel 16 and on WBUC. The agenda for this meeting can be viewed after 4 p.m. on Aug. 28, 2020.

post_text: While school buildings have been closed the past few months for the health and safety of all during the coronavirus pandemic, we would like to thank all community supporters and organizations which have continued to support our vision of helping us to ensure OCSD students are fully prepared and life ready! One of the organizations we would like to thank is the Garrett Dunsmoor Foundation for their donation earlier this school year to support the Minetto Elementary playground project. The donation was made in honor of Garrett Dunsmoor, a former Minetto Elementary student who had passed away in 2018. While the pandemic has pushed back some plans for the playground, we are excited for the inclusive playground to be an exciting place for all to play together. #OswegoCSD

post_text:
The Oswego City School District has announced its summer feeding program to provide free meals to all children ages 18 and under. Breakfast and lunch pick-up will occur between 9 and 11 a.m. Mondays to Fridays through Aug. 28 at both Fitzhugh Park Elementary and Kingsford Park Elementary schools. Children, their family member or caretaker, may pick up meals at the cafeteria doors on the Northwest side of the school buildings. When picking up meals, please practice social distance measures and wear a mask. For more information, contact the OCSD Food Service Department at (315) 341-2022.
#OswegoCSD
#SummerFeedingProgram

post_text: Congratulations to the select OCSD students who have been accepted into the next cohort of the P-TECH program through CiTi BOCES! When those students enter high school in the fall (after a small, online bridge program this summer), they will simultaneously earn a Regents diploma and an associate's degree in applied science at NO additional cost to their families. To learn more about P-TECH and how incoming OCSD 8th graders may apply to the program next year, visit: https://www.citiboces.org/domain/71 #OswegoCSD

post_text: The artistic talent of Oswego City School District students in elementary, middle and high school may now be viewed through the first-ever Virtual District Art Fest. An online gallery of work created by students is available for their peers, family, friends and greater Oswego community and beyond to see. Despite the coronavirus pandemic closing school buildings for the health and safety of all, students have continued to create artwork at home through lessons from OCSD art teachers and their own inspiration. Check out our website, www.oswego.org for the full story! #OswegoCSD #OCSDHeartsTheArts

post_text: Beginning June 16, the Hillside entrance to Buccaneer Boulevard will be closed off to staff and the public. For safety reasons, only construction vehicles will utilize the entrance, as crews continue work on the already-voter-approved capital construction project. Additionally, there will be no diagonal parking on Buc Blvd, and the road will also be closed after the entrance to the parking lot at Leighton Elementary. This will allow vehicles to enter into the parking lot or cafeteria entrance at FLS. Until further notice, all vehicles will enter from Liberty Street, which will be two ways instead of one way. #OswegoCSD

post_text: Good morning. You all should have received the budget postcard with pertinent date information for the upcoming school budget vote. A budget newsletter will be in your mailboxes in the coming week or so, but please remember that all voting will occur via absentee ballots. Those will be mailed out this Friday, and they must be returned to the school district by 5 p.m. June 9. Absentee ballots may be returned one of two ways: mailed back in a stamped envelope provided with the ballot OR dropped off at the OCSD ballot box, which will be available from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. Mondays to Fridays, from June 1 to June 9. The ballot box will be located outside of the OCSD education center offices, located at the Leighton Elementary School playground entrance (1 Buccaneer Blvd., Oswego). #OswegoCSD

post_text: We had a handful of Oswego High School students compete in the Oswego County Virtual Envirothon last week and their hard word paid off, as they tied for second place! post_text: Buc Pride remains alive and well! You can help show your support for the Oswego City School District and all of its students, teachers, faculty/staff, administrators and community members by adding the Buc Pride Facebook profile frame, as pictured right here on the district profile. post_text: OHS seniors: we know the third marking period isn't how you had envisioned some of the last moments of your high school education and your Oswego City School District journey. post_text: Great things happen when several OCSD staff members and community businesses come together to help feed children in the greater Oswego area! Since schools have been closed to help prevent the spread of the novel coronavirus, we have collectively distributed 22,476 meals! C's Farms has loaned us their refrigerated truck, while Eagle beverage has donated hundreds of gallons of juice that we have dispersed to families. Huhtamaki has donated thousands of containers that they specially made for schools during this time that we can use to hold meals. Many local businesses have donated food to feed our staff and volunteers that are working on putting the meals together as well as dispersing them. Those businesses include: Dunkin Donuts, Lighthouse Lanes, D&S Landscaping, Oscar Roofing and Gino & Joes Pizza. #OswegoCSD

Their orchestra teachers noted their hard work, perseverance and dedication to learning each musical piece and growing their own orchestral personal skill sets. post_text: As a community we will get through this. As a partner in the community, the Oswego City School District will help where, and when, needed. We are proud to collaborate with SUNY Oswego faculty member Dan Tryon and several others in the community on an effort to 3-D print face shields for local healthcare workers as they treat patients and help combat the coronavirus. The district has three 3-D printers currently set up to assist with the process, and several OCSD technology teachers have volunteered their time. #OswegoCSD

post_text:
Minetto Elementary School kindergarten teacher Rachel Little brought the perfect teaching assistant into her classroom for a recent academic unit on animals: a chicken.

Little, who has chickens at her home, brought one chicken into her classroom to help her young students better connect to their Core Knowledge Language Arts lesson. The kindergartners learned about various animals through informational text about pigs, sheep, cows and chickens.

Through the lessons, the students learned new vocabulary and all about life cycles of animals, among other related information. #OswegoCSD

post_text:
Students in Sandy McCann‚Äôs first-grade classroom at Leighton Elementary School were over-the-moon with a recent hands-on learning activity.

As a culmination activity to the students‚Äô academic unit on astronomy, they created moons with craters out of handmade clay and a rocket that launches using student power. During the first grade Listening and Learning domain of astronomy, the students learned that gravity keeps them on Earth while in outer space gravity varies. The young, aspiring astronomers also studied the phases of the moon, all about astronauts, the first moon landing, and the space race between the United States of American and the country formerly known as the USSR.

McCann said her students were thrilled to learn about the various constellations, such as Orion, the hunter, and the Big and Little Dippers. They also discussed why Pluto is not considered a planet, so now there are eight planets. Students also learned that our sun is the center of our universe and our closest star. #OswegoCSD

post_text: Minetto Elementary first-graders had a recent visit from President George Washington, who spoke about the importance of the character trait of honesty. The students learned from President Washington about him cutting down the cherry tree and how he could not tell a lie. The first-graders listened as he discussed his impact on the country and how the nation‚Äôs government runs today with the Constitution and Bill of Rights. The special visitor mentioned the importance of how Freedom of Speech and Freedom of Assembly and how they tied into Martin Luther King, Jr. and the recent day off of school. Teacher Stephanie Albee said the opportunity was a great way to talk about the impact of people in history and how they still impact the world today and people‚Äôs futures. #OswegoCSD

post_text: Throughout the month of December, the Oswego High School National Honor Society collected donations for the Human Concerns Center, Inc., the community's local food pantry. NHS members decided to collect toiletries, including: soap, shampoo, toothbrushes, toothpaste, deodorant, feminine hygiene products and laundry detergent to assist with many needs for several Oswego families. Over 300 items were collected. This is the third year the student group has completed this project, which has grown each year. The event exemplifies service, which is one of the main NHS pillars. Pictured are OHS Juniors Amelia Rastley and Madison Jones, who represented the OHS NHS chapter on drop-off day at the pantry, with a volunteer from the agency. #OswegoCSD #OCSDCommunityConnections

post_text: The opportunities for our students to give back this holiday season are just amazing! The Oswego High School girls' junior varsity and varsity teams recently collaborated for the teams' annual charity free throw event, where players collected pledges and donations and then tried to sink as many as free throws as they could during a recent practice. Each player had the chance to land 100 shots each. Thousands of dollars from this event are raised each year to help ease the stress of the holidays on several local, OCSD families. Coaches also said the event sets the tone for team-bonding and collaborative efforts. #OswegoCSD #OCSDAthletics #OCSDCommunityConnections

post_text: Fourth-grade students at Minetto Elementary School were engrossed in learning about how animals stay alive in the winter. Guest presenter Mr. Gramlich taught the children how in the winter the water is warmer at the bottom and in the summer the water is warmer at the top. He shared that fur, feathers and fat help the animals stay warm and to notice that when the leaves start to change, the animals will also start to change. Mr. Gramlich shared a raccoon tail, deer skull and other animal bones. #OswegoCSD #LearningInAction

post_text:
We are thrilled that Dolly Parton's Imagination Library program is now available in all parts of Oswego County. Thanks to the efforts of the Literacy Coalition of Oswego County and the United Way of Greater Oswego County, children right here in our own community may build their own at-home library from birth up to age five. Parents and guardians just need to enroll their child in the program by picking up a brochure at one of our elementary schools or by visiting https://imaginationlibrary.com/

This program is sure to grow students engaged in literacy and help families bond over reading, both initiatives which the Oswego City School District is proud to support. #OswegoCSD

post_text:
Minetto Elementary School fourth-graders recently participated in a BreakoutEDU activity where they were tasked with solving ‚ÄúHalloween Haunted House Gets Ghosted.‚Äù

In small groups, students worked together as they utilized problem-solving, critical thinking, math and teamwork skills to help save parents from turning into pumpkins before time was up. Upon completion of each of the five tasks involved, students were required to unlock each of the five locks and save the day.

Amy Sullivan, fourth-grade teacher, offered thanks to library media specialist Kimberly LeRoy for her creation of the enrichment activity.

post_text: Congratulations to our Oswego High School OCAY League team! They earned first-place honors during the first OCAY League event of the 2019-2020 school year! Throughout the "Lit Pitch" competition, teams from schools in Oswego County were challenged to create a story idea for a young adult book, and then pitch their creation to a panel of judges, acting as real publishers. Each team had to create a book cover, a story synopsis, and a character portrait to support their story idea. Various other mini challenges and fun took place during the friendly competition! #OswegoCSD

post_text:
A final cohort of Oswego City School District teachers recently completed a six-day Language Essentials for Teachers of Reading and Spelling (LETRS) training, which brought the total number of OCSD-trained teachers to 52.

Throughout the recent opportunity, the teachers learned more about the five essential components of effective reading instruction, as well as writing with a focus on translating research to classroom application. Information learned focused on the cognitive process of learning to read and the teaching practices proven to be most effective in preventing and remediating reading difficulties, including dyslexia.

Pictured are OCSD teachers from various elementary schools who attended the most recent LETRS training with national LETRS trainer Mary Beth Glover.

#OswegoCSD
